@Bean is a method-level annotation

In other words, without relying on Spring to automatically detect and create beans,we can:

1. Explicitly create and configure beans by writing methods annotated with @Bean inside a class annotated with  @Configuration.

2. Spring will automatically manage the lifecycle of these beans, inject them wherever needed, and handle dependencies between them.

@Bean ka kaam hai method ke through object create karke Spring container me register karna.
means object hm bnate h, aur Spring usko bean bna ke manage karta h.

@Bean is used when we need  manual control over object creationor when the class cannot be modified.


@Bean tab use hota h jab object ka creation hm control karna chahte h ya class hmari nhi hoti h.

//------Program 1--------------

//Student.java file

    package com.example.demo;
    
    public class Student{
        public void display(){
            System.out.println("Student Bean Created Using @Bean");
        }
    } 


// AppConfig.java

    package com.example.demo;

    import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
    import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

    @Configuration
    
    public class AppConfig{
        @Bean
        pubblic Student student(){
            return new Student();
        }
    }

// DemoApplication.java

    package com.example.demo;
    import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.AutoWired;
    import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
    import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;

    @SpringBootApplication

    public class DemoApplication{
        @Autowired 

        Student student;

        public static void main(String args[]){
            var context=SpringApplication.run(DemoApplication.class, args[]);

            DemoApplication app=context.getBean(DemoApplication.class);
            app.studnet.display();
            
        }
    }